carli@narziss.sni.de (Carlin) writes:


>The following table has been found scratched in various geographically
>distant sites such as Cirencester (England), Pompeii, and Dura-Europos
>(Mesopotamia):

>Latin       (English)
>R O T A S  (the wheels)
>O P E R A  (with care)
>T E N E T  (holds)
>A R E P O  (Arepo)
>S A T O R  (the sower)

>N.B.: This table reads the same from
>several directions. When rearranged
>the following cross can be drawn:

>             A

>             P
>             A
>             T
>             E
>             R
>A  P A T E R N O S T E R  O
>             O
>             S
>             T
>             E
>             R

>             O

>PATER NOSTER (Latin for "Our Father")
>A for Greek Alpha
>O for Greek Omega

>Rev 1:8 "I am the Alpha and the Omega," says the Lord God,
>"who is, and who was, and who is to come, the Almighty." (NIV)

How do you get from the sqaure to the cross?


